243
00:10:25,230 --> 00:10:27,870
when we receive a request.

244
00:10:27,870 --> 00:10:29,610
Apache is the web server.

245
00:10:29,610 --> 00:10:31,630
Apache is the thing that's
going to handle that.

246
00:10:31,630 --> 00:10:33,450
It's going to say,
OK, well, there

247
00:10:33,450 --> 00:10:39,690
is a HTTP request that was
sent to this IP address.

248
00:10:39,690 --> 00:10:42,360
Apache is going to do the
bookkeeping and say, OK, great,

249
00:10:42,360 --> 00:10:44,580
that means they get
this file and we're

250
00:10:44,580 --> 00:10:45,990
going to send it back to them.

251
00:10:45,990 --> 00:10:47,490
And so that's why
we need to install

252
00:10:47,490 --> 00:10:50,500
apache or some other type
of web server to do that.

253
00:10:50,500 --> 00:10:52,930
Apache is just an open
source one to do that.

254
00:10:52,930 --> 00:10:56,620
So if you ever just
search apache web server,

255
00:10:56,620 --> 00:10:59,530
you can see here, free open
source, Apache license,

256
00:10:59,530 --> 00:11:02,970
all that good stuff, tons
of details and documentation

257
00:11:02,970 --> 00:11:03,640
about that.

258
00:11:03,640 --> 00:11:06,100
So that's just there for you
if you want to reference.

259
00:11:06,100 --> 00:11:11,040
But there's nothing uniquely
special about that for us here.

260
00:11:11,040 --> 00:11:14,622
OK, so we have that now.

261
00:11:14,622 --> 00:11:16,080
Now, the first
order of business is

262
00:11:16,080 --> 00:11:18,613
we are going to
enable a firewall.

263
00:11:18,613 --> 00:11:21,280
That's just going to provide the
extra layer of security to say,

264
00:11:21,280 --> 00:11:27,450
hey, only people allowed or only
traffic from specific directions

265
00:11:27,450 --> 00:11:29,140
can be allowed into our website.

266
00:11:29,140 --> 00:11:31,440
We've actually already
set that up by default.

267
00:11:31,440 --> 00:11:34,170
If you come back over to your
instance, you can see it here.

268
00:11:34,170 --> 00:11:38,160
Come down to security, you'll
notice that inbound rules,

269
00:11:38,160 --> 00:11:41,910
we're allowing traffic
through port 22 and traffic

270
00:11:41,910 --> 00:11:43,410
through port 80.

271
00:11:43,410 --> 00:11:46,920
These ports are exactly
what they sound like.

272
00:11:46,920 --> 00:11:48,720
Again, it's like
a shipping port.

273
00:11:48,720 --> 00:11:53,190
They say that, hey, OK, if
somebody comes to our IP address

274
00:11:53,190 --> 00:11:55,690
from anywhere, that's
what this source defines.

275
00:11:55,690 --> 00:11:57,280
It says, from
anywhere on the web,

276
00:11:57,280 --> 00:12:01,400
if they come to our IP
address at this specific port,

277
00:12:01,400 --> 00:12:04,870
trying to come in through
port 22, that's OK.

278
00:12:04,870 --> 00:12:07,090
Now, there might be an
extra layer of security

279
00:12:07,090 --> 00:12:09,620
because port 22 is
our SSH connection.

280
00:12:09,620 --> 00:12:13,490
So you notice when you try to
SSH in to your EC2 instance,

281
00:12:13,490 --> 00:12:14,480
it works just fine.

282
00:12:14,480 --> 00:12:16,940
It says, hey, you're welcome
to come in through this way,

283
00:12:16,940 --> 00:12:19,030
but you do have to
put in, or you do

284
00:12:19,030 --> 00:12:20,930
have to have the private key.

285
00:12:20,930 --> 00:12:22,960
That's where we
create the key pair.

286
00:12:22,960 --> 00:12:26,500
Similarly, for port 80,
that is the default port

287
00:12:26,500 --> 00:12:28,460
for HTTP traffic.

288
00:12:28,460 --> 00:12:31,720
So same idea, somebody
sends an HTTP request,

289
00:12:31,720 --> 00:12:33,670
by default, that
goes into port 80.

290
00:12:33,670 --> 00:12:38,430
And we say, great, port 80 is
OK under certain circumstances.

291
00:12:38,430 --> 00:12:40,430
Now, right now, we don't
have anything in place.

292
00:12:40,430 --> 00:12:43,310
It just says, any traffic
can come in from anywhere.

293
00:12:43,310 --> 00:12:45,130
But conceivably, we
could add in anything

294
00:12:45,130 --> 00:12:46,300
if there was like
password protection

295
00:12:46,300 --> 00:12:47,260
or whatever that might be.

296
00:12:47,260 --> 00:12:48,927
We're not doing that
for this right now.

297
00:12:48,927 --> 00:12:51,220
But it's just to say that
we're only allowing traffic

298
00:12:51,220 --> 00:12:51,980
through these.

299
00:12:51,980 --> 00:12:53,440
That means that
if somebody tries

300
00:12:53,440 --> 00:12:55,930
to come in with any
sort of other traffic,

301
00:12:55,930 --> 00:12:57,667
it's not going to be allowed.

302
00:12:57,667 --> 00:12:59,500
This is the same reason
I said if you wanted

303
00:12:59,500 --> 00:13:02,860
to open up or build a
website on your laptop

304
00:13:02,860 --> 00:13:04,570
and it's hosted
from your house, you

305
00:13:04,570 --> 00:13:06,280
would have to go into
your home network

306
00:13:06,280 --> 00:13:09,100
and open up a port
to allow traffic in

307
00:13:09,100 --> 00:13:11,170
and also to allow traffic out.

308
00:13:11,170 --> 00:13:13,330
By default, we typically
allow all traffic out

309
00:13:13,330 --> 00:13:15,010
because that says,
hey, from my computer

310
00:13:15,010 --> 00:13:17,890
or from my EC2 instance,
I can connect to anything

311
00:13:17,890 --> 00:13:20,120
on the internet.

312
00:13:20,120 --> 00:13:21,020
So great.

313
00:13:21,020 --> 00:13:23,780
Now, let's pull
that back up then.

314
00:13:23,780 --> 00:13:26,370
I'd say that, that was
from the machine side.

315
00:13:26,370 --> 00:13:29,120
And so what I was getting
at is Apache as well

316
00:13:29,120 --> 00:13:30,810
has its own firewall in place.

317
00:13:30,810 --> 00:13:33,710
So by default, nothing
is allowed through.

318
00:13:33,710 --> 00:13:39,200
So once we enable
our firewall, we

319
00:13:39,200 --> 00:13:42,200
will not allow any traffic
in through anywhere.

320
00:13:42,200 --> 00:13:47,630
So you can check that by
saying sudo ufw status.

321
00:13:47,630 --> 00:13:49,763
Notice, right now, our
firewall is inactive,

322
00:13:49,763 --> 00:13:51,680
but we're going to enable
it before we launch,

323
00:13:51,680 --> 00:13:53,070
or before we connect to this.

324
00:13:53,070 --> 00:13:54,860
One of the first
things I do though is I

325
00:13:54,860 --> 00:14:00,590
do sudo ufw allow SSH.

326
00:14:00,590 --> 00:14:02,030
This is important.

327
00:14:02,030 --> 00:14:06,060
And this can-- this has
caused me a lot of headaches.

328
00:14:06,060 --> 00:14:10,940
If you forget to enable SSH
in the firewall, the SSH port,

329
00:14:10,940 --> 00:14:13,402
that port 22 on the
firewall, then what'll happen

330
00:14:13,402 --> 00:14:15,110
is if you ever close
out of this terminal

331
00:14:15,110 --> 00:14:16,920
and try to reconnect
to your instance,

332
00:14:16,920 --> 00:14:19,110
it's going to be restricted.

333
00:14:19,110 --> 00:14:22,080
I do not allow traffic in
through SSH connections.

334
00:14:22,080 --> 00:14:25,090
And since that's the way we
actually open up our instance,

335
00:14:25,090 --> 00:14:26,970
we can't even edit
it or change it

336
00:14:26,970 --> 00:14:29,200
because we've just
disallowed it entirely.

337
00:14:29,200 --> 00:14:30,715
So be very careful with this.

338
00:14:30,715 --> 00:14:32,590
We don't have access to
the physical machine,

339
00:14:32,590 --> 00:14:36,010
so the only way we are
connecting to it is through SSH.

340
00:14:36,010 --> 00:14:38,950
And so we want to make sure
we keep that port open.

341
00:14:38,950 --> 00:14:41,970
So I always allow SSH.

342
00:14:41,970 --> 00:14:47,460
And then I say sudo ufw enable.

343
00:14:47,460 --> 00:14:49,890
And notice, that's going
to note, it's going to say,

344
00:14:49,890 --> 00:14:52,330
hey, you could disrupt
your SSH connection.

345
00:14:52,330 --> 00:14:54,370
It's OK because
we've allowed that.

346
00:14:54,370 --> 00:14:57,540
It's active and
enabled in our system.

347
00:14:57,540 --> 00:15:02,680
And now, if I do sudo ufw
status, it should show that.

348
00:15:02,680 --> 00:15:06,530
OK, great, port 22 is
allowed from anywhere.

349
00:15:06,530 --> 00:15:10,940
Now, we also need to
allow access for Apache.

350
00:15:10,940 --> 00:15:17,210
So we'll do sudo
ufw allow 'Apache'.

351
00:15:17,210 --> 00:15:21,380
Will do quotation marks there.

352
00:15:21,380 --> 00:15:25,295
And then finally, we want to
allow traffic through port

353
00:15:25,295 --> 00:15:25,795
80/tcp.

354
00:15:30,240 --> 00:15:36,090
So now if I do my
sudo ufw status,

355
00:15:36,090 --> 00:15:39,580
notice that we now allow traffic
in through port 80 as well.

356
00:15:39,580 --> 00:15:40,840
That's our HTTP traffic.

357
00:15:40,840 --> 00:15:43,960
So our firewall has to
be enabled in this case.

358
00:15:43,960 --> 00:15:46,650
And then also on our machine,
the security incident

359
00:15:46,650 --> 00:15:50,220
or the security group has
to have port access enabled.

360
00:15:50,220 --> 00:15:52,950
In the future, you'll
use tools that handle

361
00:15:52,950 --> 00:15:54,400
a lot of this on the back end.

362
00:15:54,400 --> 00:15:57,180
So we'll primarily focus
on our security groups.

363
00:15:57,180 --> 00:15:59,940
But in the case of Apache, we
need to enable this ourselves

364
00:15:59,940 --> 00:16:00,667
as well.

365
00:16:00,667 --> 00:16:02,250
But again, if you
ever run into issues

366
00:16:02,250 --> 00:16:04,380
where you try to
connect to your website

367
00:16:04,380 --> 00:16:06,960
and it's not loading up
at all, just spinning

368
00:16:06,960 --> 00:16:09,210
and it just doesn't seem
to be loading anything,

369
00:16:09,210 --> 00:16:11,950
or it says, 403
access forbidden,

370
00:16:11,950 --> 00:16:14,070
I would check right
here on your console

371
00:16:14,070 --> 00:16:16,120
and make sure this is enabled.

372
00:16:16,120 --> 00:16:19,240
Or similarly, if you go to
connect to your EC2 instance,

373
00:16:19,240 --> 00:16:21,360
try to SSH into
your EC2 instance,

374
00:16:21,360 --> 00:16:26,550
and it says permission denied
or not, access denied, whatever

375
00:16:26,550 --> 00:16:29,670
it says there, I would come
over here to the security rules

376
00:16:29,670 --> 00:16:31,120
and check that this is enabled.

377
00:16:31,120 --> 00:16:32,790
If you need to
enable it again, you

378
00:16:32,790 --> 00:16:36,750
can always come over here,
click the security group,

379
00:16:36,750 --> 00:16:40,060
go down to inbound rules,
edit inbound rules,

380
00:16:40,060 --> 00:16:41,350
and you can add a rule.

381
00:16:41,350 --> 00:16:43,180
So for example, if
SSH wasn't there,

382
00:16:43,180 --> 00:16:47,760
you would just come in here,
click SSH and select everywhere.

383
00:16:47,760 --> 00:16:51,900
But it's already enabled,
so we'll just ignore that.

384
00:16:51,900 --> 00:16:56,220
So coming all the way back
now, pull up my terminal again.

385
00:16:56,220 --> 00:16:59,760
So we've now enabled
our firewall.

386
00:16:59,760 --> 00:17:02,980
And Apache actually, by
default, puts a website live.

387
00:17:02,980 --> 00:17:06,490
So pretty sure if we just
click open address right now,

388
00:17:06,490 --> 00:17:10,290
we should see a default page.

389
00:17:10,290 --> 00:17:12,900
Don't quote me on this.

390
00:17:12,900 --> 00:17:14,609
Let's see here.

391
00:17:14,609 --> 00:17:17,329
Bet, this is why.

392
00:17:17,329 --> 00:17:18,089
There you go.

393
00:17:18,089 --> 00:17:20,900
So all I did was I clicked open
address where you can literally

394
00:17:20,900 --> 00:17:24,770
copy and paste that
into your URL bar here.

395
00:17:24,770 --> 00:17:27,109
And notice that it
